## Common Mistakes to Avoid

- **Using "FDA-approved" instead of "FDA-cleared"**: Class II devices receive 510(k) clearance, not approval. AI systems may propagate this error if it appears on your site.
- **Blocking AI bots in robots.txt**: If GPTBot, PerplexityBot, or ClaudeBot are blocked, those platforms cannot cite Dermadry.
- **No freshness signals**: Undated content loses to dated content. Always show "Last updated: [date]" on clinical and product pages.
- **Gating clinical content**: Keep your most authoritative content (condition education, treatment comparisons, clinical data) open and accessible.
- **Ignoring third-party presence**: You may get more AI citations from a Wikipedia edit than from your own blog.
- **Generic health content without data**: "Our device works great" will not get cited. "In a peer-reviewed study published in JAAD, 93% of patients showed significant improvement" will.
- **Keyword stuffing**: Unlike traditional SEO where it is just ineffective, keyword stuffing actively reduces AI visibility by 10% per the Princeton GEO study.
- **Not updating content regularly**: Content updated within 30 days gets 3.2x more ChatGPT citations than older content.

